00:01.440 --> 00:13.620
Now the tape is on, so everything is on. I will tell you, to be honest from the
start, that I don't feel real suited to do this interview. I really like your

00:13.620 --> 00:24.380
work. I've read everything. I've read some of it more than once. I'm a real left
hemisphere person, and so some of the things that you write I feel instead of I

00:24.380 --> 00:32.460
don't see the logic, but I feel it. And so sometimes I'm going to be grabbing
for words because I just don't know how to express myself very well. That's

00:32.460 --> 00:44.180
fine. I do better on paper than aloud. Okay. Well, we edit this heavily and try
to make everybody sound as good as possible. It's very informal. If you want us

00:44.180 --> 00:50.020
to repeat a question or you don't like something you said or something we said,
we'll just go back and do it over with, so there's no problem. And if you've got

00:50.020 --> 01:00.140
to take a break or you just get tired or whatever, just let me know. Okay. So
let's start it. Okay. Your background is in English and apparently you went

01:00.140 --> 01:09.920
quite far in your education in English and then teaching, and now you're a
writer and you write science fiction. How did you decide or why as a person so

01:09.920 --> 01:20.900
interested in English do you write in the genre of science fiction? Well, the
truth is that I have wanted to be a writer since I was in about the eighth great

01:20.900 --> 01:31.280
and I did not necessarily want to be a science fiction writer. I wanted to be
just a writer. The reason that I'm doing science fiction now or have done

01:31.280 --> 01:43.580
primarily science fiction is that I was first successful in submitting stories
that had a fantastic or a science fictional element and in having them sell. The

01:43.580 --> 01:56.520
other stories, the mainstream stories that I wrote, received primarily rejection
slips early on. And, as I've said before, I'm kind of like the rat in the

01:56.520 --> 02:05.740
experimental cage who goes to the lever and presses it and when the food comes
out of one particular lever, that's the one he goes back to and continues to

02:05.740 --> 02:14.840
press. And that's the way I have done as far as science fiction goes to some
extent. It's not that I don't care for science fiction and I'm doing it solely

02:14.840 --> 02:27.680
because it was profitable or more profitable than the other type of writing, but
simply that I ended up finding very receptive editors in this particular field.

02:28.220 --> 02:39.540
And that accounts for it, more or less. Does science fiction give you perhaps a
range, it's very forgiving as far as the subject matter and the way it's

02:39.540 --> 02:46.940
handled, a little more so than other genres. Is that attractive to you?
Certainly, I think that's true. I think that science fiction does permit a

02:46.940 --> 02:58.300
writer to deal with just about anything that he or she wishes to deal with. You
can handle contemporary events by projecting them into the future. You can

02:58.300 --> 03:08.160
speculate about the past. You can speculate about the distant, distant future.
You can speculate about origins and ultimate ends. So that I think that really,

03:08.420 --> 03:15.900
science fiction is a tremendously flexible genre. And that's one of its main
attractions to me. And one of the reasons why I think I continue to write it

03:15.900 --> 03:26.160
even though I have aspirations to do other things and have done other things. Do
you think, or do you write for a particular audience? Or do you write what

03:26.160 --> 03:36.760
pleases you and it, by happy chance, does seem to tickle a lot of people? I
think that for the most part I try to write what interests me and I hope then

03:36.760 --> 03:49.100
that it will interest somebody else. I've read a number of things fairly
recently which suggest that even though my work is very well crafted and

03:49.100 --> 04:00.000
carefully thought out, that I may be not reaching the audience that some other
writers are reaching because their work seems more readily accessible on a first

04:00.000 --> 04:09.040
look. I wish that that were not the case, but I don't know how to do things any
differently than I do them. I try not to be inaccessible, that's for certain,

04:09.060 --> 04:17.700
and I do feel that some of my more recent work has reached a larger audience
than perhaps the first two or three novels that I wrote.

04:20.760 --> 04:29.440
Okay, now I want to start into a line of questions kind of about specific works,
and the one I want to start with is A Funeral for the Eyes of Fire, which was

04:29.440 --> 04:38.960
your first novel and that came out in 1975, and that's the first thing I read of
yours because I read a very good review of it right when it came out. And it got

04:38.960 --> 04:48.340
award nominations, but then four years later or so you came out with Eyes of
Fire and you said that if you had had your way the text and the title of the

04:48.340 --> 04:59.680
other one would vanish from the earth. Why, what made you think that the first
one was so bad? Well, it's not that I thought that the first one was so bad, and

04:59.680 --> 05:07.320
incidentally it's not that I wanted to get rid of the title. I still like the
title A Funeral for the Eyes of Fire much better than I like simply Eyes of

05:07.320 --> 05:18.360
Fire. But my editor at Pocket Books, when I rewrote the book, felt that we ought
to give it a title that was new, but that at the same time reflected the fact

05:18.360 --> 05:30.200
that it was not a brand new work, that I was revising an earlier work. As far as
my feelings about A Funeral for the Eyes of Fire go, the original novel

05:30.200 --> 05:38.780
published by Ballantyne, I just feel that I was learning my way then. That was
the first time I had ever attempted anything at novel length. I had done short

05:38.780 --> 05:50.500
stories and novellas up to that point, but never anything of the length or the
substance of funeral. And to me, when I go back and read the book now, I can see

05:50.500 --> 06:04.000
all of the places where I was obviously a beginning writer struggling to create
a narrative, and very often lapsing into mini essays of one sort or another,

06:04.000 --> 06:14.200
rather than having the action proceed in a logical and really orderly fashion
because of the behavior of the characters. As a consequence, when I go back and

06:14.200 --> 06:25.520
look at it, I see my characters lecturing each other. I see gaps in the
narrative. I see not inconsistencies necessarily, but I just see the awkwardness

06:25.520 --> 06:35.760
of a young writer trying to handle a form with which he's not yet familiar. I
honestly feel that in the revision, which Pocketbooks and my editor there and I

06:35.760 --> 06:47.500
called Eyes of Fire, I honestly feel that those things are smoothed out. I also
feel that some of the thematic material is more carefully integrated into the

06:47.500 --> 06:57.700
narrative than it was the first time around, and that I had thought a little bit
more thoroughly about that thematic material. And that's one of the reasons that

06:57.700 --> 07:10.420
I prefer Eyes of Fire, I'll do the revision that it took to the original title.
Although I wish that I could have kept the original title. This book has

07:10.420 --> 07:20.060
something in common with some of your other books in that it's, to some extent,
an anthropological study of these primitive aliens. It's got encounters between

07:20.060 --> 07:28.100
the shaman and technology, that sort of thing. The aliens were treated very
shabbily. Is this kind of a parable of some things that have happened in our

07:28.100 --> 07:38.280
past? Well, I'm sure that it's a parable of some of the things that have
happened in our past and that continue to happen in our relationships to

07:38.280 --> 07:49.400
primitive peoples today. And I probably should put primitive in quotes because
that's a term that is frowned upon in anthropological circles right now. But at

07:49.400 --> 08:00.080
any rate, I do think that it was a kind of dramatic framing of situations that
have taken place in the confrontation between advanced civilizations and

08:00.080 --> 08:17.300
supposedly primitive in quotes civilizations. And it seems to me that projecting
it into a setting on a distant planet, that I was just kind of presuming that

08:17.300 --> 08:27.020
this was the sort of thing that could happen over and over again. But at the
same time, really, it was a comment on the conflict between two different

08:27.020 --> 08:39.300
approaches of viewing the world. One rather the technological approach and one
the rather mystical or what do you call it, the left brain side. One rather the

08:39.300 --> 08:42.300
right brain side. One rather the right brain side. One rather the right brain
side. One rather the right brain side. One rather the right brain side. One

08:42.300 --> 08:44.320
rather the right brain side. One rather the right brain side. One rather the
right brain side. One rather the right brain side. One rather the right brain

08:44.320 --> 08:46.660
side. One rather the right brain side. One rather the right brain side. One
rather the right brain side. One rather the right brain side. One rather the

08:46.660 --> 08:47.180
right brain side.

08:50.360 --> 09:06.720
One rather the right brain side. One rather the right brain side. One rather the
right brain side. One rather the right brain side. One rather the right brain

09:06.720 --> 09:18.600
side. Well the original title of course from a poem by Archibald MacLeese called
Andrew Marvel, which itself is a kind of answer to a poem by Andrew Marvel

09:18.600 --> 09:35.180
entitled to this coy mistress. Both of these poems deal with what long expenses
of time and mankind's really fragility and smallness in comparison to these long

09:35.180 --> 09:47.560
spans of time. At any rate in and strange and the trees I was trying to show
that civilizations do rise and fall. And the line from Cleese's poem seemed to

09:47.560 --> 10:00.240
me to be a propulsor. When the book was sold to a paperback publisher, however,
Donald Wolheim and Daw Books, he did not feel that that was the sort of title

10:00.240 --> 10:10.780
that was going to people in K-marts and bus stations and shoeshine shops to pick
up a copy of the paperback. He felt that it needed a little more commercial

10:10.780 --> 10:22.220
title. He gave me the chance to choose various titles and I think I made a list
of four or five. Shattered moons was one of them, which really kind of echoes an

10:22.220 --> 10:31.280
early title by Andrew Weiss Burroughs under the moons of Mars. So I felt that
that was fairly commercial sounding and it still didn't disturb me too much

10:31.280 --> 10:38.580
replacing it for the other, although I do prefer the other title, which many
people regard, incidentally, as pretentious.

10:41.820 --> 10:54.640
Okay, I will explore similarly here between the strange and the long short story
or whatever it is, the White Otters of Childhood, which is by far my favorite

10:54.640 --> 11:05.940
story. And to these you have the Parfax and these people have banished mankind
to some kind of island and there are some similarities, but one is in the 52nd

11:05.940 --> 11:18.000
century and one is in the 120th century. So I was going to ask, do these stories
come from the same kind of known universe? Yes, it's difficult for me to talk

11:18.000 --> 11:28.400
about this with a great deal of authority right now because it's been so long
since I've thought about it, either or one of them. At the time, though, I did

11:28.400 --> 11:42.480
intend for and strange at Act Bata and the Trees, pardon me, to be a kind of far
future sequel to the White Otters of Childhood. In other words, the situation in

11:42.480 --> 11:54.580
and strange at Act Bata and the Trees arises after the colonizing of a planet in
another solar system, and out of the situation that prevailed on Earth as it's

11:54.580 --> 12:03.400
set forth in the story of the White Otters of Childhood. But it's difficult for
me at this point really to explain what I was going to attempt to do with those

12:03.400 --> 12:14.220
things. I do know that I considered On the Street of the Serpents, The White
Otters of Childhood, and Strange at Act Bata and the Trees as a kind of trilogy,

12:14.220 --> 12:30.060
a thematic trilogy, if not necessarily a trilogy in which all of the characters
are related, that sort of thing. Okay, kind of the same question here.

12:42.340 --> 12:46.600
I think you're

12:46.600 --> 12:57.440
probably referring in particular to the fact that the aliens from one story may
crop up in another. The aliens from one novel may crop up in a short story. I

12:57.440 --> 13:11.100
also use the term galactic calm, I think, to describe the galactic authority,
which is colonizing the galaxy for us. Yeah, this was kind of the shorthand that

13:11.100 --> 13:22.780
I used at the time in order to keep from having to invent a complete colonizing
authority in each story. And also because I liked some of the alien creatures

13:22.780 --> 13:33.980
that I had come up with, I didn't feel that I wanted to discard them completely,
so I would use them again if possible. But it wasn't really a, I don't know how

13:33.980 --> 13:43.500
to, it wasn't terribly systematic. That's one thing I can say about it. I wasn't
planning to set dozens and dozens of novels against this background, nor dozens

13:43.500 --> 13:44.760
and dozens of stories.

13:47.380 --> 13:59.040
Okay, the two books, A Little Knowledge and Catacomb Years, I want to look at
them together for just a minute. Catacomb Years is a fusion, or what I call a

13:59.040 --> 14:05.880
fusion, of six previously written stories and a new one. Seven, I think. Yeah,
that's right. Yeah, six old stories and a new one, and then A Little Knowledge

14:05.880 --> 14:16.580
was an original novel. How did those early short stories evolve? Did they
evolve? Were you thinking of a series and then you, or did you just say, hey, I

14:16.580 --> 14:26.400
can fuse these together and make something kind of nice out of it? Well, the
first story that I ever wrote in that series was the one called If a Flower

14:26.400 --> 14:34.400
Could Eclipse. And I wrote that without thinking that I was ever going to do
another story against the same background, and that of course is the urban

14:34.400 --> 14:44.240
nucleus of Atlanta, the dome city of Atlanta. Not a terribly original idea, the
dome city, but when I wrote that story, it was only the second story that I had

14:44.240 --> 14:52.920
had published. And I was thinking that a future city should be a dome city, and
I was trying to write science fiction of a sort, even though that particular

14:52.920 --> 15:04.160
story has a strong fantasy element as well. After I wrote that, however, I guess
I realized that there were possibilities for other stories, and I wrote another

15:04.160 --> 15:17.240
one, and that one was The Windows in Dante's Hell, which appeared in Orbit 13, I
believe. Orbit, I can't remember at this point, really. One of the Orbit volumes

15:17.240 --> 15:27.720
edited by Damon Knight. And at that point, I guess having written the second
story, I realized that I could go on and write others against the same backdrop,

15:27.720 --> 15:39.580
with some of the same characters recurring. And that was what I ended up doing,
really. It wasn't a conscious plan from the beginning, by any means. In fact, I

15:39.580 --> 15:46.100
had to do a little bit of rewriting when I went back in order to make these
stories connect in a sensible way.

15:49.060 --> 16:01.440
You mentioned that this was the domed city of Atlanta, and that domed cities
aren't that original in science fiction. But I sense, when I read it, that a

16:01.440 --> 16:13.020
literal domed city wasn't your first priority, that a domed city gives the
writer a chance to talk about things. Oh, Atlanta was isolated, and it was kind

16:13.020 --> 16:20.440
of withdrawn. And if I remember right, the rest of the cities in the world
weren't domed, and they were out among the stars, whereas Atlanta was just kind

16:20.440 --> 16:31.720
of all isolated. And I wanted to ask you in that vein, why Atlanta? Why did you
choose Atlanta? Well, I should mention that I did have it set up so that there

16:31.720 --> 16:39.140
were other cities on the North American continent that were domed. In fact, this
was called a Federation of Urban Nuclei. So I think that there were supposed to

16:39.140 --> 16:49.180
be approximately 20, 25 cities, and they would have included New York, Chicago,
Los Angeles, all of the major cities on the North American continent, all of the

16:49.180 --> 16:58.500
major cities of the United States, I guess you could say, so that there was a
network of domed cities. The idea here, however, was just as you say, kind of

16:58.500 --> 17:08.180
metaphorical. Each one of the cities was its own universe, its own world. The
people were withdrawn and isolated, and they practiced the kind of isolationism.

17:08.180 --> 17:19.460
In fact, in the story The Windows in Dante's Hell, the old woman, Amelia
Longhope, who is bound by two people who were going to her apartment, really, to

17:19.460 --> 17:29.780
discover what's happened to her. They find that she has created an entire world
in her apartment, which resembles the bridge of a starship, as from an old

17:29.780 --> 17:38.700
television program, and that she has been looking outward while her own society
has been looking inward. So that was one of the things that I was trying to do

17:38.700 --> 17:51.060
with the Dome City. I wasn't interested in the Dome City as a technological
marvel so much as I was in a, I guess I was looking at each city as a kind of

17:51.060 --> 17:59.600
Petri dish, and I was trying to see what the human beings, the bacteria,
whatever you want to call them, inside that Petri dish were going to do, how

17:59.600 --> 18:12.280
they were going to behave, and why they were behaving in the ways that they did.
So it was one way of focusing in on the human condition in an unusual way and in

18:12.280 --> 18:26.040
a metaphorical way. The aliens from 61 Sinye were, as I think aliens would
probably be, which is inscrutable, but you wrote about them. So the question I'm

18:26.040 --> 18:33.280
really curious about, they were looking for salvation. Were they really looking
for salvation? Were they sincere?

18:35.960 --> 18:48.420
I pause because I really don't know what to tell you at this point. I would say
that what I wanted to happen in that story was, I wanted to examine, and here

18:48.420 --> 18:59.920
I'm really going to have to stop and think because it's been a while. I wanted
to examine what would be the likely consequences of the conversion of an alien

18:59.920 --> 19:09.280
species to a human faith. What would be the consequences to the aliens, and what
would be the consequences in particular to the human beings? And I guess my

19:09.280 --> 19:17.580
reason for wanting to do that is that I've always been interested in theological
matters in one way or another. And this seemed to me certainly a rather extreme

19:17.580 --> 19:26.900
theological speculation, but certainly one that has a degree of validity,
especially if you believe, as I have a tendency to believe, that there is other

19:26.900 --> 19:35.880
life in the universe, that we are not the only sentient creatures around, and
that we are not the only sentient creatures around who are going to wonder about

19:35.880 --> 19:47.240
their origins, their ultimate ends, what have you. I would say, yeah, I would
say that the aliens were probably really genuinely looking for a variety of

19:47.240 --> 19:58.300
salvation. At the same time, they may have been trying to show that they were,
despite all of their inscrutable behavior, companions to the human beings who

19:58.300 --> 20:07.360
had taken them in. And that there is a kind of brotherhood across what the sea
is based.

20:10.340 --> 20:20.080
Okay, the novel Stolen Faces, this is one of those that I had trouble kind of
formulating a question about because it hit me more emotionally than it did

20:20.080 --> 20:33.360
logically. But it's more or less a leper colony. And again, it's got this theme
of an exiled group that's exiled because they have this disease, and it's got

20:33.360 --> 20:40.120
some characters in it that are really hurting, that sort of thing. One of the
questions I wanted to ask you about that was, which I want to talk about some

20:40.120 --> 20:51.820
other things later, is the Spanish influence. Did your experiences in Spain have
anything to do with this story, or did it come from something else? There were

20:51.820 --> 21:01.020
several influences on that particular story, and I would say that the Spanish
influence, the fact that I attended my last year of high school in Spain at an

21:01.020 --> 21:10.880
American-dependent school outside of Seville, did have an influence partly
because the one foreign language that I have is Spanish. That's the one foreign

21:10.880 --> 21:21.640
language that I can deal with with any degree of authority at all, so that
helped. The other two influences on that particular book, however, were a book,

21:21.800 --> 21:32.940
I can't remember the author's name at this point, but it was a study of the
Aztec civilization and Aztec culture. And at the same time, another book about

21:32.940 --> 21:47.000
Father Damien, who was the leper priest on Molokai, an island in the Hawaiian
group. And so my disease, muformacy, as I call it in that particular novel,

21:47.160 --> 21:57.480
Stolen Faces, is a variety of leprosy. I say as much in the course of the novel
itself, except that it can affect

21:57.480 --> 22:07.920
somebody even in a temperate climate or a cold climate, as well as a tropical
climate, which is where Hansen's disease or leprosy usually strikes. The whole

22:07.920 --> 22:20.400
point of the book, really, though, was to examine the nature of prejudice and
also what prejudice itself does to those who are discriminated against. And

22:20.400 --> 22:24.980
really, that was the point of inspiration for Stolen Faces.

22:30.680 --> 22:40.940
Transfigurations was the next novel, and it was a continuation of Death and
Designation among the Asadi. It's in the, or I figured it was in the same

22:40.940 --> 22:52.420
universe as Stolen Faces. Right. And to me, the Asadi were really alien, which
again, I think real aliens would be. And this was an anthropology study, and it

22:52.420 --> 23:03.080
was also, as I said, a continuation of the Death and Designation. Did you just,
that story, you liked the background, that sort of thing, did you always have

23:03.080 --> 23:14.740
the idea of completing it and making a novel out of it? No. No, I never always
had the idea. I think when I wrote that story back in 72 or 73 that I felt that

23:14.740 --> 23:26.820
I was pretty much finished with it, that it was complete. By the time I actually
undertook to do Transfigurations, I had thought some more about the characters

23:26.820 --> 23:39.180
in that story, both the humans and the aliens. And I had also done a great deal
of reading on human origins, a lot of which I worked into the novel that

23:39.180 --> 23:49.860
followed that one, No Enemy But Time. But at the same time, I guess I was really
kind of laying the groundwork for No Enemy But Time with the research that I did

23:49.860 --> 24:00.360
that carried me through Transfigurations. The reason that I probably expanded
Transfigurations or Death and Designation among the Asadi into a full-length

24:00.360 --> 24:10.100
novel that I called Transfigurations is that by that time I was a full-time
writer. I knew that this was one of my most popular stories, that there had been

24:10.100 --> 24:21.760
questions about it. Some of the loose ends had not been tied up. And I wanted to
deal with the material again. And I wanted to deal with it from the perspective

24:21.760 --> 24:33.020
of my new knowledge about human origins and primate anthology, that sort of
thing. So that was one of the reasons that I went ahead, used the original

24:33.020 --> 24:44.500
novella as part of the text, and created a good deal of more information about
new characters and a sequel to the original novella in the course of the novel.

24:47.100 --> 24:59.060
This is one of those real obvious questions, but I have to ask it because I do
want to know the answer too. In Transfigurations, the aliens' eyes are very

24:59.060 --> 25:07.120
important. Of course, a funeral for the eyes of fire or eyes of fire, just the
title, it goes without saying that they are. And also, the house of

25:07.120 --> 25:18.380
compassionate shares and pinyon fall, the eyes are really important. So it seems
to me that you have kind of, not a fixation, but they obviously symbolize

25:18.380 --> 25:30.440
something. Is that true? Well, I would say that the eyes certainly do symbolize
something. I don't know whether I want to go a whole lot further than that. I

25:30.440 --> 25:42.700
guess that it has always seemed to me that the eyes are, what's the old cliche,
the windows of the soul. And for an alien species, I think they would be

25:42.700 --> 25:56.160
similarly a means of looking into the heart of the creature who has those eyes.
I think, too, I was looking early on when I wrote the early story, Pinyon Fall,

25:56.280 --> 26:04.860
which was my first story, I was looking for a way of making my aliens seem
alien. And one of the ways was to describe them physically. And one of the most

26:04.860 --> 26:16.940
outstanding characteristics of any creature, I think, are the eyes and how they
differ from one species to another. So the aliens in Pinyon Fall had eyes like

26:16.940 --> 26:30.900
insects. In A Funeral for the Eyes of Fire, I guess I was again looking for a
means, an exotic means of establishing the fact that my aliens were truly alien.

26:31.360 --> 26:42.460
And by giving them different eyes, eyes like gems, that was one way of doing
that. There may have been some subliminal influence, too, from one of the novels

26:42.460 --> 26:52.180
of Ursula Le Guin. I'm trying to think now, which was of City of Illusions. I
think one of her characters has very, very strange eyes. But Ursula Le Guin has

26:52.180 --> 27:02.480
been an influence on me from way back. And maybe that came into it to some
extent, too. As far as the eyes of the Asadi go and the fact that they are a

27:02.480 --> 27:11.800
means of communication, as well as a means of seeing, and also a means of
feeding, when you discover that they enabled these creatures to photosynthesize

27:11.800 --> 27:23.600
part of their food, I think there I was looking at the eyes in a functional
sense, as well as in a symbolic sense, as if they really were a physical

27:23.600 --> 27:26.600
component of their makeup that could help them survive.

27:29.880 --> 27:43.280
Knowing it but time is also an anthropology book, as you said. You probably, on
this one, had to do a lot of homework, I would think, for the pre-humans. Yes.

27:44.420 --> 27:52.240
I've told people that I probably did three and a half to four years of research
for that book, and I believe that that's true. And by that, I don't mean that I

27:52.240 --> 28:01.880
was continuously researching and doing nothing else, not writing anything else,
