30:18.120 --> 30:27.840
character who was somehow attuned to the distant past, and particularly the
distant past of Pleistocene, East Africa. And as a consequence, I came up with a

30:27.840 --> 30:37.960
character who had vivid dreams, even from his infancy on, about this particular
period, so that his attunement to the Pleistocene in East Africa would make it

30:37.960 --> 30:50.380
possible later on for an Air Force time program to actually send him back bodily
to that period, or a simulacrum of that period, as I explain it in the book. So

30:50.380 --> 30:59.820
that much I knew I was going to have to give him. After that, however, I was
really kind of on my own to come up with the sort of person that he happened to

30:59.820 --> 31:09.500
be, and that unfolded for me gradually in the composition of the book, and I was
kind of surprised to discover who Joshua Campa really was, or the kind of

31:09.500 --> 31:19.460
character that he really was. And that was one of the nice things about writing
the book, too. Did you write the book in the order that we read it? In other

31:19.460 --> 31:27.280
words, there are some alternating chapters, the past, the present, the past, the
present. Did you write it that way, or did you write all the past and all the

31:27.280 --> 31:42.500
present, and then cut them up? To tell you the truth, I think I wrote
alternating chapters. There were a couple of occasions when perhaps the episodes

31:42.500 --> 31:53.780
in the past, I may have split them up and inserted a chapter from the present or
from the near future. But for the most part, I actually did go back and forth. I

31:53.780 --> 32:00.780
did not write them in the order that they actually occur in the book, however.
As a matter of fact, the first thing in the book, the prologue, I wrote at the

32:00.780 --> 32:11.360
very end, after I had completed the composition of the entire novel. I might
also add here that David Hartwell, my editor at Timescape, was instrumental in

32:11.360 --> 32:24.360
